Changes (S − Sref
) of the SED (S) with respect to its nonpathological value (Sref
) can be considered as the mechanical signal driving bone remodeling. However, a certain level of the signal must be exceeded before the bone responds. This level s defines the so-called dead zone within which no bone remodeling is expected;20 s has the value of 0.75, a level that was found to produce realistic predictions for hip implants.19 According to Martelli et al.,21 the evaluation of RBRES (risk for long-time excessive bone resorption) parameter can give a prediction of bone loss (RBRES<−100%) or bone deposition (RBRES>+100%). The computed values are reported in Table 4.
